The Otiothopinae representatives are distinguished from other palpimanids by having a male palp without accessory terminal sclerites and conductor, and by the internal female genitalia with only one or two membranous spermathecae, without ducts or other accessory structures (
). Among otiothopines, the genus
Fernandezina Birabén, 1951
presents 15 described species, all from South America (
). Species of
Fernandezina
are distinguished from other otiothopines by the posteriorly expanded opisthosomal scutum in males and by the unexpanded femora I in both sexes (
).

All known 

Fernandezina
species

are epigean taxa known from forested environments, including Caribbean (

; 

), Andean (

), Amazonian (

; 

), restingas and Atlantic (

) forests. In these environments, the reported specimens were collected either with pitfall traps (e.g., 

; 

), searching in or sifting the leaf litter (e.g., 

; 

; 

). Recently, spider samplings carried out inside and outside limestone caves in the Brazilian semiarid domain revealed the first hypogean 

Fernandezina
species.

Along with this cave species, a second epigean 

Fernandezina
species

is described in the present study, based on specimens collected in the same expedition.

The examined specimens are deposited in the following Brazilian collections (acronyms and curators in parentheses): Coleção de História Natural da Universidade Federal do Piauí , Floriano, Piauí (CHNUFPI, J.F. Vilela); Centro de Coleçıes Taxonômicas da Universidade Federal de Minas Gerais , Belo Horizonte, Minas Gerais ( UFMG , A.J. Santos). The specimens were examined submersed and preserved in 80% ethanol. Female internal genitalia were examined after digesting soft tissues using pancreatin solution (described by
). Description style follows the most recent taxonomic papers regarding
Fernandezina
(e.g.,
